This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with stereo matching and depth-map prediction from stereo video. The use of deep learning and recurrent neural networks also suggests that it could belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The paper also mentions the ability of the network to adapt to previously unseen environments, which suggests that it could belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes a novel method for stereo matching, which could place it in the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions benchmark datasets such as KITTI and Middlebury stereo, which suggests that it could belong to the computer vision and pattern recognition (cs.CVPR) sub-category.
